Now I'll execute the network_fetcher tool to retrieve data from the API. I'll use the default URL as specified in the environment rules.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I need to parse the raw data from the network_fetcher before validation since the validator requires parsed data. I'll execute the data_processing_parser tool next. Since the network_fetcher likely returned raw data, I'll parse it using the default URL.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I need to validate the parsed data structure. Since the validator requires a schema and we don't have one, I'll use a minimal default schema that expects an object with some data. This is a reasonable default for testing purposes.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll execute the network_fetcher tool as requested to fetch API data:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
